  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Support for life-saving health interventions for the most acute needs in under-served areas of Deir-ez-Zor, Ar Raqqa,</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project will serve children (girls and boys) and women with a package of essential health services, mainly through mobile medical teams (MMTs) run through a combination of partners including local NGOs, faith-based organizations, and dDirectorates of health in the targeted districtsareas. The medical teams are composed of specialized physicians, pediatricians, nurses and midwives who will provide the core package of primary care, including the provision of basic consultations, treatment of communicable diseases, and health education to vulnerable children and women in prioritized locations with severe unmet needs for health care services. The teams will also screen children and women to check their nutrition status and identify cases that need to be referred to specialized nutrition centers for treatment and follow-up. In addition, they will provide health education for key child survival behaviours to caregivers, such as on breastfeeding and young child feeding practices, and referral of missed children for routine immunization. The complicated medical cases will be referred to more specialized level of health care, including children with disabilities.
A special attention will be focused on Deir-ez-Zor to scale up integrated health promotion interventions as part of the PHC package for the control of outbreaks of communicable diseases. This governorate has in recent times been at the center of outbreaks of vaccine preventable diseases (polio and measles), water-borne (watery and bloody diarrhea) and typhoid fever amongst others. The ongoing limited interventions in this domain must be intensified to save lives and prevent continuous spread to surrounding governorates. An estimated 59,000 direct beneficiaries will be targeted for this intervention living in severity scale 4-5-6 areas in the two targeted governorates.</narrative>
  </description>
